<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="508" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1483,2014]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1591,1617]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Jin &amp; Bu &amp; Ye, 2022" authorityName="Li &amp; Jin &amp; Bu &amp; Ye" authorityYear="2022" box="[330,590,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvisetae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[330,590,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Pseudovelia curvisetae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[599,690,1591,1617]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[599,690,1591,1617]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
appears to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ye, Polhemus &amp; Bu, 2013" authorityName="Ye, Polhemus &amp; Bu" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiseta">
<emphasis box="[1062,1194,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. longiseta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ye, Z. &amp; Polhemus, D. A. &amp; Bu, W. J." pageId="1" pageNumber="508" pagination="290 - 318" refId="ref7712" refString="Ye, Z., Polhemus, D. A. &amp; Bu, W. J. (2013) A taxonomic contribution to the genus Pseudovelia Hoberlandt, 1951 (Hemiptera: Veliidae) from China, with descriptions of ten new species. Zootaxa, 3636 (2), 290 - 318. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3636.2.4" type="journal article" year="2013">Ye, Polhemus &amp; Bu, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Andersen, 1983" authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1983" box="[262,566,1627,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccula">
<emphasis box="[262,379,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. buccula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen, N. M." box="[385,566,1627,1653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" pagination="253 - 268" refId="ref7414" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1983) The Old World Microveliinae (Hemiptera: Veliidae). I. The status of Pseudovelia Hoberlandt and Perivelia Poisson, with a review of Oriental species. Entomologica Scandinavica, 14, 253 - 268. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631283 X 00254" type="journal article" year="1983">Andersen, 1983</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Jin &amp; Bu &amp; Ye, 2022" authorityName="Li &amp; Jin &amp; Bu &amp; Ye" authorityYear="2022" box="[693,835,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvisetae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[693,835,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. curvisetae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[843,932,1627,1653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[843,932,1627,1653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ye, Polhemus &amp; Bu" authorityYear="2013" box="[1237,1368,1627,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiseta">
<emphasis box="[1237,1368,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. longiseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its two pairs of relatively long, curved and black setae on the pygophore (
<figureCitation box="[953,1038,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–64" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1165,1189]" captionTargetBox="[234,1369,196,1128]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[205,1381,181,1141]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59–64. Pygophore of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 59. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 60. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 61. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 62. P. plauta sp. nov.; 63. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 64. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816747" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816747/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
). This species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1983" box="[212,328,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccula">
<emphasis box="[212,328,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. buccula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its relatively straight hind tarsal segment I (
<figureCitation box="[851,933,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
), whereas hind tarsal segment I of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1983" box="[1321,1437,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccula">
<emphasis box="[1321,1437,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. buccula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is relatively curved (
<figureCitation box="[385,471,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). In addition, the middle femur of 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Jin &amp; Bu &amp; Ye, 2022" authorityName="Li &amp; Jin &amp; Bu &amp; Ye" authorityYear="2022" box="[866,1010,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvisetae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[866,1010,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. curvisetae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1018,1109,1735,1761]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1018,1109,1735,1761]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
does not have a row of long hairs compared to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1983" box="[438,555,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccula">
<emphasis box="[438,555,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. buccula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[570,707,1771,1798]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,1001,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-396@7.[152,1436,993,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Middle legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 23. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 24. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 25. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 26. P. plauta sp. nov.; 27. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 28. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816731/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Figs. 23, 25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="509" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1483,2014]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,1941]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="509" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,530,1807,1833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Description. Apterous male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[548,619,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[253,1330,191,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[241,1345,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Habitus of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 1. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 2. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 3. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 4. P. plauta sp. nov.; 5. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 6. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816717" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816717/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Color: ground color yellowish-brown, head dark-brown, clypeus yellowish, rostrum brown, buccula brown; antennal segments I–IV dark-brown; pronotum yellowish- brown, posterior part of pronotum with dense, black spots; lateral part of metanotum yellowish-brown, black-rimmed; legs (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 17–22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[159,1414,193,1138]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17–22. Fore legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 17. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 18. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 19. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 20. P. plauta sp. nov.; 21. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 22. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816727/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Figs. 19</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[193,223,1915,1942]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,1001,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-396@7.[152,1436,993,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Middle legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 23. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 24. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 25. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 26. P. plauta sp. nov.; 27. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 28. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816731/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[234,263,1915,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">31</figureCitation>
) mainly brown, basal parts of femora pale-brown, apical parts of femora infuscated, tibiae and tarsi darkbrown, grasping combs black; mediotergites I–VI brown, with black margins; mediotergite VII black; connexiva dull-orange; lateral part of mediotergite I, medial parts of mediotergites II, III, VI and VII with prominent silvery pubescence; abdominal segment VIII (
<figureCitation box="[595,691,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,226,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,211,1681]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 35. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 36. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 37. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 38. P. plauta sp. nov.; 39. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 40. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816737/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Figs. 37</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[705,736,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–52" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,201,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-18@11.[151,1436,181,1808]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 47–52. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 47. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 48. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 49. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 50. P. plauta sp. nov.; 51. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 52. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816743/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">49</figureCitation>
), pygophore (
<figureCitation box="[897,981,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–64" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1165,1189]" captionTargetBox="[234,1369,196,1128]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[205,1381,181,1141]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59–64. Pygophore of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 59. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 60. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 61. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 62. P. plauta sp. nov.; 63. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 64. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816747" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816747/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
) and proctiger yellowish, each of them weakly infuscated apically. Structural characteristics: body medium-sized, rather slender, bearing short, suberect, black setae, area around eyes and antennal segment I covered by relatively few, long, suberect, grayish setae. Head short and wide, relatively perpendicular to thorax, without inflection; buccula clearly visible, produced posteriorly; eyes bare except for the presence of two ocular setae. Pronotum relatively broad, bearing dense punctures on the posterior portion of pronotal lobe; hind margin of pronotum slightly rounded, anterior margin slightly emarginated; metanotum completely hidden beneath pronotal lobe except laterally. Fore tibia (
<figureCitation box="[1061,1143,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[159,1414,193,1138]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17–22. Fore legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 17. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 18. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 19. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 20. P. plauta sp. nov.; 21. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 22. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816727/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) with dense, short, brown setae, medial portion of venter on fore tibia with distinct process, grasping comb relatively strong; middle femur and tibia (
<figureCitation box="[264,346,438,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,1001,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-396@7.[152,1436,993,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Middle legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 23. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 24. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 25. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 26. P. plauta sp. nov.; 27. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 28. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816731/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
) with dense, short, brown setae, apical part of middle tibia with few long, suberect, brown setae; hind leg (
<figureCitation box="[259,341,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
) strongly modified, hind femur and tibia with dense, short, brown setae, hind tarsus much longer than hind tibia, hind tarsal segment I longest and slightly curved, about 1.06 times length of hind tibia, with a tuft of more than 5 very long, black bristles arising from basal part, ventral arolium bristle-like; mediotergites almost flat, connexiva relatively narrow and slightly raised, abdominal segments III–VI approximately rectangular; mediotergites I–V subequal in length; abdominal venter flat; end of abdomen covered with relatively dense, curved and brown setae. Genital segments: abdominal segment VIII (
<figureCitation box="[800,894,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,226,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,211,1681]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 35. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 36. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 37. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 38. P. plauta sp. nov.; 39. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 40. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816737/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Figs. 37</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[906,936,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–46" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1427,216,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[151,1436,211,1738]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 41–46. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 41. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 42. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 43. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 44. P. plauta sp. nov.; 45. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 46. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816739" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816739/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">43</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[949,980,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–52" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,201,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-18@11.[151,1436,181,1808]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 47–52. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 47. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 48. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 49. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 50. P. plauta sp. nov.; 51. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 52. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816743/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">49</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[991,1020,654,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–58" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,182,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-21@12.[151,1436,181,1795]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 53–58. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 53. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 54. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 55. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 56. P. plauta sp. nov.; 57. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 58. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816745" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816745/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">55</figureCitation>
) relatively stout, about 1.68 times as long as wide, hind margin with dense, long and blackish-brown hairs, ventrally with a sub-rectangular depression, hind margin of depression with short, suberect, slender and brown setae, lateral margins of depression with a pair of relatively dense, short, slightly curved and blackish brown setae; pygophore (
<figureCitation box="[1053,1134,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–64" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1165,1189]" captionTargetBox="[234,1369,196,1128]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[205,1381,181,1141]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59–64. Pygophore of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 59. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 60. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 61. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 62. P. plauta sp. nov.; 63. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 64. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816747" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816747/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
) nearly rectangular, with a flat apex, lateral margins of pygophore with few, short, curved and brown setae and a tuft of dense, short and brown setae, posterior part with two pairs of relatively long, curved and black setae; proctiger small, posterior part with dense, short, brown setae; parameres symmetrical, stick-like, middle part slightly twisted.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,395,906,932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Apterous female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[411,479,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1323,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[254,1333,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Habitus of Pseudovelia spp. (apterous females). 7. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 8. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 9. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 10. P. plauta sp. nov.; 11. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 12. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816721/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Color: similar to male. Structural characteristics: body medium-sized and relatively wide, structure of head including antenna as in male; fore tibia without process and grasping comb, hind tibia and tarsus not modified, venter of hind tarsal segment I without a tuft of bristles; abdomen pleurally and ventrally without special modifications, connexiva converging posteriorly and touching caudally; end of abdomen raised in lateral view, gonocoxa I elongate, proctiger brown, with dense, short hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,453,1086,1113]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Macropterous female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[468,551,1086,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1847,1871]" captionTargetBox="[166,1410,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[151,1436,181,1770]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13–16. Habitus of Pseudovelia spp. (macropterous form). 13. P. buccula Andersen, 1983, macropterous male; 14. P. buccula Andersen, 1983, macropterous female; 15. P. curvisetae sp. nov., macropterous female; 16. P. plauta sp. nov., macropterous female. Scale 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816725/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Color: similar to apterous female. Structural characteristics: Body size similar to apterous females, structure of head including antenna as in apterous female; pronotum relatively wide, nearly pentagonal; hemelytra grayish, with a slender white spot on basal part; fore tibia without process and grasping comb, hind tibia and tarsus not modified, venter of hind tarsal segment I without a tuft of bristles; abdomen hidden beneath hemelytra except lateral margin of connexiva, structure of abdomen including connexiva, gonocoxa and proctiger as in apterous female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1941]" box="[199,553,1303,1329]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,441,1303,1329]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Macropterous male:</emphasis>
unknown
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,568,1338,1365]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Measurements. Apterous male.</emphasis>
Body length 2.63–2.70 (
<typeStatus box="[847,951,1339,1365]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">holotype</typeStatus>
: 2.63), head width: 0.60–0.62, head length: 0.34–0.41, head width about 1.52 times head length; antenna about 0.78 times as long as body, length of antennal segments I–IV: 0.58, 0.48, 0.47, 0.49; pronotum width: 0.84–0.86, pronotum length: 0.53–0.58, about 1.60 times as wide as long; length of grasping comb 0.34, about 0.46 times tibial length; length of leg segments (femur, tibia and tarsus): fore leg: 0.74, 0.74 and 0.41, middle leg: 1.00, 1.06 and 0.67 (0.25+0.42) hind leg: 1.05, 0.90 and 1.48 (0.95+0.53). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[297,500,1518,1544]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Apterous female.</emphasis>
Body length: 2.95–3.08, head width: 0.65–0.66, head length: 0.43–0.49, head width about 1.51 times head length; antenna about 0.57 times as long as body, length of antennal segments I–IV: 0.55, 0.33, 0.32, 0.47; pronotum width: 0.85–0.89, pronotum length: 0.50–0.54, about 1.57 times as wide as long; length of leg segments (femur, tibia and tarsus): fore leg: 0.79, 0.73 and 0.44, middle leg: 1.00, 1.02 and 0.66 (0.22+0.44), hind leg: 1.14, 1.14 and 0.83 (0.36+0.47). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[620,881,1662,1689]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Macropterous female.</emphasis>
Body length: 2.95, head width: 0.65, head length: 0.44, head width about 1.48 times head length, antenna about 0.58 times as long as body, length of antennal segments I–IV: 0.55, 0.34, 0.34, 0.47; pronotum width: 1.29, pronotum length: 1.11, about 1.16 times as wide as long; length of leg segments (femur, tibia and tarsus): fore leg: 0.81, 0.71 and 0.43, middle leg: 1.00, 1.02 and 0.63 (0.21+0.42), hind leg: 1.12, 1.17 and 0.80 (0.36+0.44).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="509" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1843,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Li &amp; Jin &amp; Bu &amp; Ye" authorityYear="2022" box="[576,691,1843,1868]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvisetae">
<emphasis box="[576,691,1843,1868]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">curvisetae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (from Latin, meaning curved setae) refers to the two pairs of long, curved, black setae on the hind margin of male pygophore, which are clearly visible at the end of abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,650,1914,1941]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1941]" box="[199,650,1914,1941]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1914,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,426,1915,1941]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[441,530,1915,1941]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation box="[553,637,1914,1941]" captionStart="FIGURE 65" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1950,1974]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,715,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-283@14.[151,1436,705,1926]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 65. Geographical distribution of species of Pseudovelia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816749" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816749/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="509">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
